to everyone who would send me tells, but I'll admit now that I often just ignore the tells. I don't generally mean it to be rude, but depending on the zone I'll literally get 10 tells a minute for stuff that the person could (more likely than not) live without. I'd spend more time responding to tells nicely, and enjoying the back-and-forth arguments on why I really should help that person out, than playing the game...<br><br>I'm also finding that my generosity is getting a bit thinner, as it seems that every other person I buff out of niceness adds me to their friends list - and 'expects' more help in the future.  Seems that being nice can often be a no-win-situation.<br><br>On a very few occasions I've used the druid to make a few plat, when I was particularly low. The best strategy is to go to a zone and just /auction out your services. Generally travelling across zones to help people is a big waste of time. If you're a cleric, with 39 rez, perhaps go sit outside KC and /auction 39 rez available at KC, 30 plat. That way you don't have the uncomfortable situation of 'negotiating' a donation and people know up front what is expected. I think it appears less greedy and more entreprenureal, but that's just me. <br><br>If you only rez people in the same zone, you can also expect cash up-front usually - either from them, or their group mates. Enough people rip off service-providers that I think it's perfectly acceptable to have a cash-up-front policy - it's how the RL world works, anyways.<br><br>Just for the record, typically what I've seen for rez prices is something like this: 39 rez is 50p, 49 rez is 100p, 56 rez is either 100 or 150 (but it's been rare that a 56+ cleric has accepted a donation, WHEN they've been willing to help out - never assume generosity =). There are certainly variations, but this has seemed the most common standard I've seen...<br><br>Best Regards,<br>Alaryas Ix`Stynia - 59 Revenant <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFAFA><td n